The KwaZulu-Natal Cooperative Governance and Traditional
Affairs (Cogta) Department has brought in another administrator to turn the
fortunes of the ailing Msunduzi Municipality around. Martin Sithole replaces Scelo Duma whose term ended last
month. He has three diplomas in financial management, business
management and public finance management and administration. He also has an
honours degree in Public Administration, advanced certificate programme in
management development and Bachelor of Business Administration degree from
Newport University (Janus University). He also has a national certificate in
Public Finance Management and Administration and an executive leadership
municipal management programme certificate. According to Sitholeâ€™s CV, he has worked as a municipal
manager, acting municipal manager and in other roles in at least one district
and two local municipalities around the province. Among these is Uthukela
District as acting municipal manager and manager from 2012 until March 2022. Between 2002 and 2008 he has worked as municipal manager in
the Ubuhlebezwe Municipality and as executive director: business support centre
at Hibiscus Coast Municipality. Sithole is not new to the current task of being an
administrator. He has held the position in seven other municipalities. These
are Okhahlamba, Umvoti, Imbabazane, Indaka and Mpofana municipalities between
2011 and 2019. Between 2016 and 2020 he was an administrator in
Umkhanyakude and Uthukela district municipalities respectively. He has professional membership in various formations like
the Black Management Forum, Institute of Business Advisors, Institute of Local
Government Management, South African Institute of Tax Practitioners and the
Institute of Directors of South Africa.